 people shall use it as a reference book and mnemonic aid. I will describe the 18 most important plants that every master of herbology and in the first place every cleric shall know who is willing to ensure the grace of Gods by using the traditional rituals.§($1,>) §§Gylvir\n\nThe Gylvir root only grows in the hottest desert areas of Tamar. Mostly the small unimposing bunch of green culms will be spilled by numerous sandstorms which rampage through the deserts so often.In almost the same manner though, it is the best time to look for the Gylvir after a sandstorm because then the bunches often become visible which were covered with sand before. Surprisingly the green culms still look fresh and green after they have been covered with sand for weeks. The secret is the far into the ground ranging roots. They consist of a whole row of corms with many side branches which lie one below the other. It is no easy work to dig out the root entirely but it is worth the effort. On the other hand\
 some of the skillful collectors let parts ofthe root remain in the deep sand to hope that a new plant grows from that. This hope is not quite unfounded and some people have already dug out the Glyvir root at the same place over years. You cut the root corm into thin slices and let them dry afterwards. During the accordant ritual these thin slices will be dug in the ground at the place of ceremony together with goldenrod powder. Thereby the god of fertility will be made merciful and the yield of herbal resources will considerably increase in the next time.§($2,<,-1) §§
